====================================================================
  INTERVIEW TIPS FOR L6 LEVEL
====================================================================

1. CLARIFY FIRST (Always!):
   - Directed or undirected?
   - Weighted or unweighted?
   - Can weights be negative?
   - Self-loops allowed?
   - Disconnected components possible?
   - Size constraints?

2. STATE COMPLEXITY UPFRONT:
   - Time AND space
   - Best, average, worst case
   - Trade-offs between approaches

3. DISCUSS TRADE-OFFS:
   - "Why Dijkstra vs Bellman-Ford here?"
   - "BFS vs DFS - which fits better and why?"
   - "Could we use Union-Find instead?"

4. CONSIDER EDGE CASES:
   - Empty graph / empty input
   - Single node
   - Disconnected components
   - Self-loops
   - Negative weights (if allowed)
   - Cycles in directed graphs

5. SCALE DISCUSSION (L6 BAR):
   - "What if graph is too large for memory?"
   - Distributed algorithms: Pregel, GraphX, GraphLab
   - Streaming algorithms for dynamic graphs
   - Approximation algorithms for NP-hard problems
   - Sharding / partitioning strategies
   - Cache locality considerations

6. CODE QUALITY (Critical at L6):
   - Clean, readable variable names
   - Helper functions for clarity
   - Handle edge cases at the top
   - Add comments only for non-obvious logic
   - Modular, testable code


